WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.760
So thank you again for being here.

00:00:10.760 --> 00:00:15.680
I'm excited to talk to you today about kind of the basics of the RStudio Connect internals

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:20.280
and sort of what's going on behind the scenes in the server and how you can manage and interact

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:21.360
with it.

00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:23.959
So we're going to cover a few different topics today.

00:00:23.959 --> 00:00:29.000
So we'll start with just a basic introduction to what is RStudio Connect, so if you're unfamiliar

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.400
or that you're new to this product, then we'll cover that briefly.

00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:38.240
Secondly, we'll talk about installation and setup and kind of what you need to do and

00:00:38.240 --> 00:00:41.599
things that you need to be aware of in order to configure the product.

00:00:41.599 --> 00:00:45.400
And then lastly, we'll dive a little bit deeper into a few different areas on some details

00:00:45.400 --> 00:00:49.560
about how the product works and some nuances that you should be aware of.

00:00:49.560 --> 00:00:54.480
As Anne mentioned, we will be doing a follow-on webinar to this one in a couple of weeks,

00:00:54.480 --> 00:00:57.799
and in that webinar, we'll actually go into a lot more detail on this third section around

00:00:57.799 --> 00:01:02.759
more details and some more things that you should be aware of if you want to manage this

00:01:02.759 --> 00:01:05.120
product in a production environment.

00:01:05.120 --> 00:01:08.680
And then we'll conclude with a demo of the product so that if you haven't seen it yet,

00:01:08.680 --> 00:01:12.720
you'll have an opportunity to get a feel for what it does.

00:01:12.720 --> 00:01:16.919
So RStudio Connect is an enterprise publishing and management platform.

00:01:16.919 --> 00:01:20.400
It can handle static and dynamic content, basically anything that you can create with

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:25.839
R, including documents, presentations, dashboards, and Shiny applications.

00:01:25.839 --> 00:01:29.080
And so one of the nice things about this is that it has push-button publishing from

00:01:29.080 --> 00:01:30.839
the RStudio IDE.

00:01:30.839 --> 00:01:34.639
And so if you're using a recent version of the IDE, you'll see this little publish button

00:01:34.639 --> 00:01:36.599
that you see here at the top right.

00:01:36.599 --> 00:01:40.480
You should be able to click that and click Publish to RStudio Connect, and if you register

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:44.519
an account on an RStudio Connect server, you'll be able to seamlessly publish documents and

00:01:44.519 --> 00:01:49.279
R Markdown documents and Shiny applications and anything else that you're producing in

00:01:49.279 --> 00:01:51.720
the IDE into Connect.

00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:55.239
It is an on-premises enterprise product, so this is not an open-source product, but it

00:01:55.239 --> 00:02:02.080
is something that you can install behind your firewall, and it's not a hosted environment.

00:02:02.080 --> 00:02:06.959
And lastly, it obviously is meant for sharing data science artifacts within your organization.

00:02:06.959 --> 00:02:12.720
So this is a sneak peek of what most of your users are going to see when they look at RStudio

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:13.720
Connect.

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:17.679
So on the right here, this is the full panel, and you can see the majority of the space

00:02:17.679 --> 00:02:20.679
is taken up on this lower left here by the Shiny application.

00:02:20.679 --> 00:02:26.960
This is what your users or you would be creating to share within your organization.

00:02:26.960 --> 00:02:31.240
Up at the top, you can see we have kind of a settings toolbar and some management there

00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:35.399
of the content, and then over on the right, you've got your settings panel, which is where

00:02:35.399 --> 00:02:38.679
you can manage, in this case, the performance of the Shiny application.

00:02:38.679 --> 00:02:41.320
You can see another screenshot separately on the left here of what it looks like to

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:45.160
manage the access controls of different content on the server as well.

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:49.160
So this is one of the key features of Connect, is that you're going to be able to go in,

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:52.360
search directly from the IDE, and now you have this web interface to be able to go in

00:02:52.360 --> 00:02:59.559
and navigate and manage your content and set who should be able to see it and who shouldn't.

00:02:59.559 --> 00:03:03.119
So in order to get started with RStudio Connect, you're first just going to want to download

00:03:03.119 --> 00:03:04.119
and install it.

00:03:04.119 --> 00:03:08.679
So you can download it from this link here, or you can find it on our website, a similar

00:03:08.679 --> 00:03:12.399
link that will let you register and download.

00:03:12.399 --> 00:03:16.440
Before you get started with Connect, you will need to install R, and depending on which

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:21.199
distribution you're using, you can either do that from your package manager, most have

00:03:21.199 --> 00:03:26.119
R, or if you're looking for a particular version of R, you can compile it from source.

00:03:26.119 --> 00:03:31.160
And then, lastly, Connect is made available as either a Debian or an RPM installer file.

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:33.279
So the installation should be pretty seamless.

00:03:33.279 --> 00:03:39.000
You should just be able to, on any of the listed distributions here, Ubuntu 12.14.16

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.520
or Red Hat or CentOS 6 and 7, you should just be able to run a command or two to be able

00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:48.399
to get Connect and any dependencies that we have up and running on your server.

00:03:48.399 --> 00:03:52.039
So at that point, you should actually have Connect installed, and it should be no more

00:03:52.039 --> 00:03:54.520
difficult than that.

00:03:54.520 --> 00:03:58.559
But one of the first things that you're going to want to do is go in and start configuring

00:03:58.559 --> 00:03:59.559
the server.

00:03:59.559 --> 00:04:04.759
And so you can see here an example on the right of what a configuration file looks like,

00:04:04.759 --> 00:04:08.119
and so these are just some of the basic settings that you might be interested in managing on

00:04:08.119 --> 00:04:09.119
the server.

00:04:09.119 --> 00:04:13.520
And so at the top here, you can see you've got your sender email, that's the email address

00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:19.760
from which you'll be sending any outgoing email on the server will be sent.

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:23.559
You've got your address, which is the URL where users should expect to come back to

00:04:23.559 --> 00:04:24.559
your server.

00:04:24.559 --> 00:04:28.040
And then you've got basic settings here around, you know, which ports do you want to be listening

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:29.040
on.

00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:32.279
If you want to use SSL, you can set up your certificate and your key, and then you can

00:04:32.279 --> 00:04:33.160
also configure authentication.

